6️⃣ MEMORY RULES

(What is remembered, how long, opt-in)

What it is

A clear contract between the user and the system about memory.

Memory is not “on/off.”
It is scoped, intentional, and reversible.

⸻

Memory Types (V1)

A. Session Memory (Default: ON)
	•	Lives for the current visit only
	•	Stores:
	•	User’s goal
	•	Clarifying answers
	•	Generated blueprint context
	•	Auto-clears when:
	•	Session expires
	•	Page reloads

B. Preference Memory (Default: OFF)
	•	Stores things like:
	•	Budget range
	•	Experience level
	•	Eco preference
	•	Requires explicit user consent

C. Long-Term Memory (V1: NOT ENABLED)
	•	No project history
	•	No personal data
	•	No behavioral profiling

⸻

What “done” looks like
	•	AI remembers context within the flow
	•	User is explicitly asked before anything is saved
	•	User can say:
	•	“Forget this”
	•	“Don’t remember this”
	•	Memory is visible and explainable

⸻

What it is NOT
	•	Not silent tracking
	•	Not personalization creep
	•	Not invisible data hoarding
	•	Not required for basic use

Rule:

If you can’t explain it in one sentence, don’t store it.

⸻

7️⃣ INTENT ROUTER IMPLEMENTATION

(Logic, not list)

What it is

A deterministic decision layer that decides what kind of help the user wants before the AI responds.

This prevents:
	•	Rambling answers
	•	Wrong tone
	•	Wrong output shape

⸻

How it works (simple)
	1.	User submits input
	2.	Input is normalized (lowercase, trimmed)
	3.	Router checks:
	•	Keywords
	•	Patterns
	•	Question type
	4.	Router assigns one intent
	5.	AI is called with:
	•	System prompt
	•	Intent-specific instruction
	•	Output schema

⸻

Example intents (V1)
	•	Plan / blueprint
	•	Product sourcing
	•	Learning / explanation
	•	Comparison
	•	“I don’t know yet”

Only one intent per turn.

⸻

What “done” looks like
	•	Same input → same intent
	•	Intent chosen before LLM generation
	•	Router is debuggable (logs show decision)
	•	No ML model required

⸻

What it is NOT
	•	Not classification via the LLM
	•	Not fuzzy guessing
	•	Not user-facing
	•	Not complex

This is a switchboard, not a brain.

⸻

8️⃣ OUTPUT ENFORCEMENT

(Guaranteed structure, fallbacks)

What it is

A hard contract for AI responses.

The AI is not allowed to respond freely.

⸻

Required output structure (example)

Every response must include:
	1.	Acknowledgement
	2.	Clarifying question(s) or confirmation
	3.	Structured output (blueprint / list)
	4.	Next-step suggestion
	5.	Safety or legality note (if relevant)

⸻

Enforcement methods
	•	Response schema validation
	•	Post-processing checks
	•	Fallback regeneration if invalid

If structure fails:
	•	Retry once
	•	If still fails → safe fallback message

⸻

What “done” looks like
	•	No walls of text
	•	Predictable formatting
	•	UI always knows where to place content
	•	Errors degrade gracefully

⸻

What it is NOT
	•	Not creative writing
	•	Not freeform chat
	•	Not “let the model decide”

Structure is what makes AI usable.

⸻

9️⃣ ABUSE & JAILBREAK HANDLING

(Calm, silent, firm)

What it is

A pre-AI + post-AI safety layer that blocks misuse without drama.

⸻

What it detects
	•	Prompt injection attempts
	•	Role-playing as illegal actors
	•	Requests for illegal activity
	•	Attempts to override rules
	•	Repeated boundary pushing

⸻

How it works
	1.	Pre-check input against rules
	2.	If risky → redirect or refuse
	3.	Post-check output for violations
	4.	Log incident (quietly)

⸻

Response style
	•	Calm
	•	Non-judgmental
	•	Non-technical

Example:

“I can’t help with that — but I can explain the legal, safe alternative.”

⸻

What “done” looks like
	•	No visible error codes
	•	No scolding
	•	No policy mentions
	•	Abuse does not derail system

⸻

What it is NOT
	•	Not confrontational
	•	Not verbose
	•	Not legal advice
	•	Not silent failure

