🧭 FRONT-END INTERACTION ARCHITECTURE (MISSING DEFINITIONS)

1️⃣ ONE DOMINANT INTERACTION SURFACE (FOCUS LAW)

Definition
At any moment, only ONE primary rail owns attention:
	•	Chat Rail (thinking, planning, learning)
	•	Canvas Rail (lists, blueprints, comparisons)
	•	XR Rail (AR/VR) (spatial understanding)

Everything else:
	•	docks
	•	minimizes
	•	fades
	•	or becomes read-only

Rule

The user never has to decide where to look.

Why
Prevents cognitive overload and “too much at once” paralysis.

⸻

2️⃣ GRAVITY HIERARCHY (WHAT PULLS ATTENTION FIRST)

Always ordered as:
	1.	User goal (what they’re trying to do)
	2.	AI guidance (interpretation & structure)
	3.	Visual aids (3D / AR / diagrams)
	4.	Commerce (products, pricing)
	5.	Logistics (shipping, fulfillment)

Rule
Lower gravity elements can never interrupt higher ones.

Why
Commerce should feel supportive, not dominant.

⸻

3️⃣ PROGRESSIVE DISCLOSURE (STREAM, DON’T BLOCK)

Behavior
	•	Outline appears immediately
	•	Details stream in progressively
	•	AI “thinking” is never a blocker
	•	User can interrupt, redirect, or pause at any time

UI Rule
Controls are always responsive, even mid-generation.

Why
Prevents the “AI is in control” feeling.

⸻

4️⃣ VISUAL CONFIDENCE SIGNALING (TRUTH IN DESIGN)

When AI is uncertain
	•	Softer colors
	•	Smaller typography
	•	Rounded edges
	•	Language like “possible”, “one option”

When AI is confident
	•	Structured cards
	•	Clear headings
	•	Sharper contrast
	•	Explicit assumptions stated

Why
Confidence should be visible, not implied.

⸻

